Democrats 'almost set the rules' for the Republican challenge of the US election

Sky News host James Morrow says the Democrats “almost set the rules” for the Republican challenge of the election and their claims of voter-fraud by pushing the Russia hoax and conspiracy at the last election. His comment comes regarding a 46-minute speech uploaded to social media where Donald Trump claimed the election had been won "illegally." President Trump dubbed this speech the "most important" he's ever given, calling out the alleged voter fraud in the November election. Mr Morrow said he believes Joe Biden did win the election, but he suspects there may have been some “monkey shines” happening behind the scenes where all the ballots came in all marked for Biden. “Let’s also remember, four years ago, the Clinton campaign and the democrats spent four years pushing the Russia hoax and the Russia conspiracy, they almost set the rules for this sort of thing.” He said the best result would be the alleged claims of voter fraud are investigated, further questioning occurs, and if irregularities are detected, they reform the electoral process. “Because otherwise every four years, America is going to go down this road of the other side, half the country, feeling like they got cheated,” he said.

Robodebt scheme 'was insufficient and has been for 26 years': Stuart Robert

Government Services Minister Stuart Robert says the practice for raising debts in the government's controversial Robodebt scheme was "insufficient and has been for 26 years", but the Morrison government took appropriate steps to rectify it. "The scale the government used this long-existing approach was higher than previous years, but its approach was exactly the same," he said. "We took advice and that showed the practice was insufficient and we took the step to stop it and repay it and that action was appropriate." When asked whether the Robodebt scheme was illegal, Mr Robert said the scheme was based on a concept of averaged income data from the ATO, which was shown to be "insufficient". "If you think back to where it began, back in 1990 with the Data Matching Bill, by 1994, averaged income data had been used by the ATO in a program of how debts were raised became normalised and the government continued that normalisation," he said. "I accept it is insufficient and it has been for at least 26 years." The Commonwealth just settled its Robodebt case for $1.2 billion, paying out and compensating tens of thousands of Australians hunted by debt collectors for money they did not even owe. Mr Robert was forced to admit that despite an original hope the scheme would recover $1.7 billion, it might not have saved the taxpayer any money.

Economy 'picking up nicely' after 'greatest fiscal shock since Great Depression'

Treasurer Josh Frydenberg says while the coronavirus pandemic has triggered the “greatest economic shock the world has seen since the Great Depression”, encouraging figures show an upward fiscal trend for Australia. “The momentum is certainly building for the economic recovery,” he told Sky News. “We saw 178,000 jobs being created last month. “We saw Australia’s AAA credit rating reaffirmed. “We saw building approvals up by 3.8 per cent. “We saw capital city house prices up by 0.7 per cent.” Mr Frydenberg said consumer and business confidence was “picking up nicely” across the board, pointing to the 3.3 per cent increase in the September quarter for GDP, which was the single largest increase since 1976. “It’s a reflection of household consumption jumping by 7.9 per cent, and household consumption is nearly 60 per cent of GDP,” he said. The treasurer went on to highlight the “temporary and targeted” nature of the JobKeeper subsidy and said there were no plans to extend the current end date from early 2021. He spruiked the welfare program as the “glue between employers and employees” during the recession and cited RBA data which reported JobKeeper helped save at least 700,000 jobs.
